            <!-- Honest disclosure of how the discipline can fail. The -->
            <!-- top-of-page banner covers generic 'this is education, -->
            <!-- not advice' framing; this section is specific to the -->
            <!-- two ways this particular strategy can underperform. -->
            <div class="dr-failure-modes">
                <div class="dr-failure-modes-label">How this strategy can fail</div>
                <p class="dr-failure-modes-intro">The discipline assumes the Power Law channel continues to bound bitcoin's price oscillations &mdash; that historical mean-reversion to the channel persists. That's an empirical observation, not a guarantee. Two specific failure modes are worth flagging concretely:</p>

                <div class="dr-failure-mode">
                    <div class="dr-failure-mode-title">1. Bitcoin breaks free of the channel.</div>
                    <p>The Power Law has held with R&sup2; above 0.95 across fifteen years and nine orders of magnitude. Past adherence does not guarantee future adherence. If price departs the channel and stays out &mdash; sustained close below the floor in a structural drawdown, or sustained close above the upper band in a regime shift &mdash; the triggers stop being meaningful.</p>
                    <p><strong>If bitcoin sustains below the floor permanently,</strong> sell triggers may never fire and you bear the full drawdown of HODL with no offsetting cash position. <strong>If bitcoin sustains above the upper band permanently,</strong> sell triggers fire but no rebuy ever materializes &mdash; you're left holding cash while bitcoin continues climbing past your sell price, indefinitely. There is no internal signal in the strategy that can tell you which regime you're in until well after the fact.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="dr-failure-mode">
                    <div class="dr-failure-mode-title">2. The rebuy fires above your prior sell price &mdash; you end up with less bitcoin than HODL.</div>
                    <p>Both triggers can execute correctly &mdash; sell at the high percentile, rebuy at the low percentile &mdash; and you can still finish a cycle holding less bitcoin than if you'd just held through. This isn't a hypothetical. It has happened multiple times in bitcoin's actual history &mdash; the table above makes this visible whenever <em>cumulative BTC</em> falls below 1.00 across a sell&rarr;rebuy pair.</p>
                    <p><strong>The most striking example:</strong> at Standard 80/50 settings, the strategy sold in March 2013 at <strong>$70</strong> (1.78&times; trend). The next rebuy didn't fire until January 2015, by which time bitcoin was trading at <strong>$234</strong> (0.73&times; trend). Both triggers fired correctly &mdash; high sell, low rebuy &mdash; but the rebuy executed at <strong>3.3&times; the prior sell price</strong>. Selling 50% at $70 and rebuying with that cash at $234 leaves you with <strong>0.65 BTC vs. 1.0 BTC</strong> for HODL through that span.</p>
                    <p>The mechanism: triggers are defined relative to the trend, but rebalancing happens in absolute dollars. When the underlying trend grows fast between cycles &mdash; which it did during bitcoin's early years &mdash; the percentile-relative low can sit higher in absolute dollars than the percentile-relative high of the previous cycle. The strategy still &lsquo;worked&rsquo; in trend-relative terms; it just underperformed HODL in absolute BTC count.</p>
                    <p>Recent cycles have been less punishing because trend growth has slowed (each successive doubling takes longer in calendar time, by construction of the Power Law) and because cycle amplitudes have compressed. But the failure mode is structural, not historical-only.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

